    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a complex, non-enzymatic browning process that gives food its wonderful flavors and colors, like when you roast a piece of meat or toast bread. It's a chemical dance, involving amino acids (the building blocks of proteins) and reducing sugars. These two components start to interact when the temperature gets high enough, which is usually above about 285°F (140°C), though the reaction can start at lower temperatures if moisture is very low. The reaction proceeds through several stages, creating hundreds of different flavor and aroma compounds—it's a chemical explosion, really!",
      "source": "target",
